<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="204" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,345,948]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,742,768]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Remarks.</emphasis>
As indicated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Santos, A. P. M. &amp; Nessimian, J. L. &amp; Takiya, D. M." box="[511,738,742,769]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Santos" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Entomology" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="458 - 480" part="41" refId="ref15814" refString="Santos, A. P. M., Nessimian, J. L. &amp; Takiya, D. M. (2016) Revised classification and evolution of leucotrichiine microcaddisflies (Trichoptera: Hydroptilidae) based on morphological and molecular data. Systematic Entomology, 41, 458 - 480. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / syen. 12168" title="Revised classification and evolution of leucotrichiine microcaddisflies (Trichoptera: Hydroptilidae) based on morphological and molecular data" type="journal article" year="2016">
Santos 
<emphasis box="[594,645,742,768]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">et al</emphasis>
. (2016)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mosely" authorityYear="1939" box="[752,903,742,768]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Acostatrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[752,903,742,768]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Acostatrichia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
probably is not a monophyletic group, but the relationships of species included in this genus remain uncertain. Currently, adult males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mosely" authorityYear="1939" box="[1200,1351,778,804]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Acostatrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1200,1351,778,804]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Acostatrichia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from those of other 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Angrisano &amp; Sganga" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[533,692,814,840]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Leucotrichiini">Leucotrichiini</taxonomicName>
genera by the combination of the following features: (1) antennal articles are simple, with the scape usually twice as long as wide; (2) each forewing costal vein is simple or bears a short bulla (not reflexed); (3) abdominal segment VII has a long ventromesal process or has two ventromesal processes; (4) abdominal segment VIII or IX bears paired posterior processes.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3731416" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3731416" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3731416/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" startId="2.[151,250,1915,1940]" targetBox="[172,1416,970,1889]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1915,1976]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,277,1915,1940]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">FIGURE 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Santos, 2020" authorityName="Santos &amp; Pes" authorityYear="2020" box="[284,487,1916,1940]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Acostatrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="araca" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[284,487,1916,1940]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Acostatrichia araca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[495,577,1916,1940]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[495,577,1916,1940]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, male holotype. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[752,783,1915,1940]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">1A</emphasis>
, head, left lateral; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[979,1008,1915,1940]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">1B</emphasis>
, head, dorsal; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1161,1192,1915,1940]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">1C</emphasis>
, right forewing, dorsal. Scale bar = 0.2 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,153,359]" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">
Here, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mosely" authorityYear="1939" box="[268,419,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Acostatrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[268,419,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">Acostatrichia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are divided into three species groups: The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mosely" authorityYear="1939" box="[988,1139,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Acostatrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plaumanni">
<emphasis box="[988,1005,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1019,1139,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">plaumanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Group (including the 
<typeStatus box="[1388,1436,153,179]" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">type</typeStatus>
species), the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Flint" authorityYear="1974" box="[294,440,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Acostatrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipenis">
<emphasis box="[294,311,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[324,440,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="204">brevipenis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Group, and the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Olah &amp; Flint" authorityYear="2012" box="[617,711,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Acostatrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerna">
